                    <li><p><m>(-8)^0</m></p></li> 
                    <li><p><m>-8^0</m></p></li>   
                    <li><p><m>3x^0</m></p></li>  
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>To simplify any of these expressions, it is critical that we remember an exponent only applies to what it is touching or immediately next to.<ol>
                 
                 <li><p>In the expression <m>\left(173 x^4 y^{251}\right)^0</m>, the exponent <m>0</m> applies to everything inside the parentheses.<md>
                    <mrow>  \left(173 x^4 y^{251}\right)^0 \amp=  1 </mrow>
                </md></p></li>
                <li><p> In the expression <m>(-8)^0</m> the exponent applies to everything inside the parentheses, <m>-8</m>.<md>
                    <mrow> (-8)^0  \amp=  1 </mrow>
                </md></p></li>   
                <li><p>In contrast to the previous example, the exponent only applies to the <m>8</m>.  We should consider that <m>-8^0 = -1 \cdot 8^0</m>, and so:<md>
                    <mrow> -8^0  \amp=  -1\cdot 8^0 </mrow>
                    <mrow>   \amp=  -1\cdot 1 </mrow>
                    <mrow>   \amp=  -1 </mrow>
                </md></p></li>   
                <li><p>In the expression <m>3x^0</m>, the exponent <m>0</m> only applies to the <m>x</m>:<md>
                    <mrow> 3x^0 \amp= 3\cdot x^0  </mrow>
                    <mrow>  \amp= 3\cdot 1 </mrow>
                    <mrow>  \amp= 3 </mrow>
                </md>Since the exponent did not apply to the <m>3</m>, the <m>3</m> stayed a <m>3</m>. </p></li>  
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>


    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Negative Exponents</title>

        <p>In <xref ref="section-exponent-rules">Section</xref>, we developed rules for simplifying expressions with whole number (<m>0</m>, <m>1</m>, <m>2</m>, <m>3</m>, etc.) exponents. These same rules apply even if the exponent is not a whole number. (Spoiler alert: The exponent rules work for all real number exponents.) We'll now focus on the meaning of negative integer exponents and how we can combine negative integer exponents with exponents rules we've previously learned.</p>

        <p>To consider the effects of negative integer exponents, let's extend the pattern we examined in the <xref ref="section-exponent-rules">Section</xref> section.  To remind us of the pattern we previously saw: each time we move down a row, we reduce the power by 1 and we divide the value by 2.  We can continue this pattern in the power and value columns, paying particular attention to the values for negative exponents:</p>

