        <p>We see from the pattern that a negative integer exponent indicates repeated multiplication by the reciprocal of its base. Simplifying these expressions, we have <me>2^{-1}  = \left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^1 = \frac{1}{2^1}, \qquad 2^{-2}  = \left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^2 = \frac{1}{2^2}, \qquad 2^{-3}  = \left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^3 = \frac{1}{2^3}</me></p>
-->
        <p>Since the choice of base <m>2</m> was arbitrary, and this pattern works for all integers, so we have the <term>negative exponent rule</term>, for any nonzero real number <m>a</m> and any whole number <m>n</m>: <me>a^{-n} = \frac{1}{a^n}</me></p>

        <remark>
            <p>What about <m>\frac{1}{a^{-n}}</m>?</p>
        <p>To show how this simplifies, we use the <xref ref="item-exponent-rules-negative-exponent-definition">negative exponent rule</xref>:
        <md>
            <mrow>\frac{1}{a^{-n}}\amp=\frac{1}{\frac{1}{a^n}}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=1 \cdot \frac{a^n}{1}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{a^n}{1}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=a^n</mrow>
        </md></p>
        </remark>

        <remark><p>Traditionally, when mathematicians simplify an expression they write the expression using only positive exponents. (Negative exponents aren't quite as <q>simple</q> as positive exponents.) This can always be accomplished using the negative exponent rule, and you will often be asked to state your final result using only positive exponents.</p></remark>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Rewrite the following expressions without negative exponents, assuming that all variables represent non-zero real numbers.
                <ol label="a.">
                    <li><p><m>5^{-3}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>4y^{-6}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>\left(\dfrac{3}{7}\right)^{-2}</m></p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><ol label="a.">
                    <li><p>We will apply the <xref ref="item-exponent-rules-zero-exponent" text="title">zero exponent rule</xref>:<md>
                        <mrow> 5^{-3} \amp= \frac{1}{5^{3}} </mrow>
                        <mrow>  \amp= \frac{1}{125} </mrow>
                    </md></p></li>   

                    <li><p>Always remember that an exponent only applies to what it is touching.  In the expression <m>4y^{-6}</m>, only the <m>y</m> has an exponent of <m>-6</m>.<md>
                        <mrow> 4y^{-6} \amp= 4\cdot \frac{1}{y^{6}} </mrow>
                        <mrow>  \amp= \frac{4}{y^6} </mrow>
                    </md></p></li>   
                <li><p>We will first use the <xref ref="item-exponent-rules-quotient-to-a-power" text="title">quotient to a power rule</xref>, and then use the <xref ref="item-exponent-rules-negative-exponent-definition" text="title">>negative exponent rule</xref>:<md>
                    <mrow> \left(\frac{3}{7}\right)^{-2} \amp= \left(\frac{3^{-2}}{7^{-2}}\right) </mrow>
                    <mrow>  \amp= \frac{7^2}{3^2} </mrow>
                    <mrow>  \amp= \frac{49}{9} </mrow>
                </md></p></li>   
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Simplify <m>\dfrac{ 3 x^{-4} }{ yz^{-2} }</m>. Do not leave negative exponents in the final answer, and assume all variables represent non-zero real numbers.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><md>
                        <mrow>\dfrac{ 3 \highlight{x^{-4}} }{ y\highlight{z^{-2}} } \amp=\dfrac{ 3 \highlight{z^{2}} }{ y\highlight{x^{4}} } </mrow>
                    </md>  Notice that the factors of <m>3</m> and <m>y</m> did not move, as both of those factors had positive exponents.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

